│ stop({"edit_points": [[5403, 5404,                                          │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.        │
│ Understanding the Issue: The issue is an assertion failure in               │
│ `ScheduleData::incrementUnscheduledDeps()` where `hasValidDependencies()`   │
│ returns false when it's expected to be true. This happens when trying to    │
│ decrement unscheduled dependencies for a control dependency that doesn't    │
│ have valid dependency information calculated yet.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s   │
│ Log: The debug log shows that the SLP vectorizer is processing a store      │
│ chain of length 4 and successfully schedules several bundles. However, when │
│ it reaches the point of handling control dependencies for a call            │
│ instruction (printf), it tries to decrement unscheduled dependencies on a   │
│ ScheduleData object that hasn't had its dependencies properly initialized.  │
│ The log shows \"SLP:   check for readiness (ctrl):  %call = tail call i32   │
│ (ptr, ...) @printf(ptr null, i32 %add1)\" right before the crash.\n\n3.     │
│ Root Cause Analysis: The problem occurs in the `DecrUnsched` lambda within  │
│ the `schedule` function. When processing control dependencies, the code     │
│ calls `Data->incrementUnscheduledDeps(-1)` without ensuring that the        │
│ ScheduleData has valid dependencies. The condition `(IsControl ||           │
│ Data->hasValidDependencies())` allows control dependencies to bypass the    │
│ `hasValidDependencies()` check, but then `incrementUnscheduledDeps()` still │
│ requires valid dependencies due to its assertion. This creates a            │
│ contradiction - control dependencies are allowed to proceed without valid   │
│ dependencies, but the increment function requires them.\n\n4. Proposed Edit │
│ Point(s):\n   + The fix is to modify the condition in the `DecrUnsched`     │
│ lambda to ensure that even for control dependencies, we only proceed if the │
│ data has valid dependencies. This prevents the assertion failure by         │
│ ensuring we don't try to increment unscheduled deps on data without valid   │
│ dependencies.\n\n5. Conclusion: The fix ensures that control dependencies   │
│ are only processed when they have valid dependency information, preventing  │
│ the assertion failure. This maintains the integrity of the scheduling       │
│ algorithm while allowing proper handling of control dependencies."})        │
